<DOC><DOCNO> AP900306-0212 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-03-06-90 0634EST</FILEID><FIRST>a e BC-WKD--EntertainmentBriefs Adv00   03-06 0294</FIRST><SECOND>BC-WKD--Entertainment Briefs, Adv 00,0301</SECOND><NOTE>$adv00</NOTE><NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE><HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD><HEAD>Entertainment Briefs</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Forty eight of the world's most gifted youngballet dancers will be introduced to the New York dance world forthe third New York International Ballet Competition.   Four rounds of competition begin June 2 with the Peasant Pas dedeux from ``Giselle'' at Lincoln Center's Alice Tully Hall.   The competition's first two weeks are devoted to repertoirestudy by the 17- to 23-year-old dancers who will come to New Yorkfrom around the world. They learn three pas de deux that areannounced upon their arrival. They also rehearse a pas de deuxdesignated by the competition _ this year the Peasant Pas de deux.   A gala performance and awards ceremony on June 25 cap theworld's only competition that requires the participants to stay forthe entire event. Even after a dancer is eliminated, he or shecontinues to take classes, attends performances and plays an activerole in the final evening's festivities.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Some of the most provocative film releases ofthe past year that have been either underrated or overlookedcommercially will be presented March 17-30 at the American Museumof the Moving Image.   The series features ``Great Balls of Fire,'' ``They Live,'' ``Ina Glass Cage,'' ``The Adventures of Baron Munchausen'' and ``84Charlie Mopic.'' Also featured will be a personal appearance by BobBalaban at a screening of his eerie psychological thriller,``Parents.''   The show, called ``A Second Look,'' presents a more aggressivelook at the current cinema than is likely to be found at theAcademy Awards. The series has been organized by David Schwartz,curator of film.</TEXT><NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE></DOC>